const sections = [
  { id: "overview",   label: "Overview" },
  { id: "core",       label: "The shared core" },
  { id: "gen1",       label: "1G — heralded + distilled" },
  { id: "gen1-anim",  label: "1G in motion" },
  { id: "gen2",       label: "2G — encoded memories" },
  { id: "gen3",       label: "3G — block-encoded transport" },
  { id: "bsm-limit",  label: "The 50 % BSM ceiling" },
  { id: "compare",    label: "Side-by-side comparison" },
  { id: "role",       label: "Network role" },
];
---

<Infographic
  title="Quantum repeaters — 1G / 2G / 3G"
  description="Quantum repeaters extend Bell-pair distribution beyond the single-fibre loss limit by chaining heralded entanglement, memory, swapping, and error correction across multiple intermediate nodes. The literature classifies repeaters into three architectural generations — 1G uses heralded generation plus two-way distillation; 2G adds quantum error correction at the memory; 3G replaces swapping with block-encoded transmission and one-way signalling. This page covers all three, plus the linear-optics 50 % Bell-state-measurement ceiling that bounds 1G generation rates."
  references={[
    "azuma-rmp-95",
    "bayerbach-sciadv-2023",
    "bennett-pra-1996",
    "jones-njp-2016",
    "kumar-ijndc-2025",
    "muralidharan-scirep-2016",
    "sangouard-rmp-83",
    "zukowski-prl-1993",
  ]}
>
  <SiteNav slot="nav" currentSubject="repeaters" sections={sections} />

  <Center max="var(--wide-width)" gutter="var(--space-3)">
    <Stack space="var(--space-6)">

      <header class="hero" id="overview" data-nav-section>
        <h1>Quantum repeaters</h1>
        <p>
          Photon loss in optical fibre is exponential in distance — about 0.20 dB/km at
          1550 nm — and the no-cloning theorem rules out the optical amplifiers that
          classical telecom uses to compensate. A direct Bell-pair link between two
          endpoints is bounded at roughly 100–200 km of standard fibre before the rate
          collapses. <strong>Quantum repeaters</strong> are the network elements that
          break that limit by inserting intermediate nodes where the link's accumulated
          loss can be reset.
        </p>
        <p>
          The literature classifies repeaters into three architectural generations,
          following Muralidharan et al. (2014, 2016) and the comprehensive Azuma et al.
          review (2023). The classification axis is which errors — loss errors,
          operation errors — each generation suppresses <em>probabilistically</em> (with
          two-way classical signalling and retries) versus
          <em>deterministically</em> (with quantum error correction at the encoding
          level). The three generations exhibit progressively weaker reliance on
          two-way classical signalling, progressively heavier hardware overhead, and
          progressively better rate scaling with
          distance <SourceNote id="muralidharan-scirep-2016" /><SourceNote id="azuma-rmp-95" />.
        </p>
      </header>

      <section id="core" data-nav-section>
        <h2>The shared core</h2>
        <p>
          The first two generations share a four-step core. A repeater chain is a
          sequence of nodes <Math tex="N_0, N_1, \\dots, N_n" /> (with Alice at
          <Math tex="N_0" /> and Bob at <Math tex="N_n" />) connected by short fibre
          segments of length <Math tex="L_0" /> each. Within that chain:
        </p>
        <ol class="rp-core">
          <li>
            <strong>Heralded entanglement generation.</strong> Each adjacent pair
            <Math tex="(N_k, N_{k+1})" /> runs a <em>heralded entanglement-generation
            protocol</em> (HEGP) — typically photonic, with the heralding signal
            announced over a classical channel. On success, the two nodes share a
            Bell pair stored in their local quantum memories; on failure, they retry.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Quantum memory.</strong> Each node holds its half of a successful
            pair while waiting for its other neighbour's pair to herald. Memory
            coherence time bounds how unsynchronised the link-level successes can be
            before the stored pair degrades.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Entanglement swapping.</strong> Each interior node performs a
            Bell-state measurement on its two stored qubits, fusing the two adjacent
            Bell pairs into one across the longer
            distance <SourceNote id="zukowski-prl-1993" />. Composed across the chain,
            this delivers an end-to-end pair between Alice and Bob.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Entanglement distillation.</strong> Operation errors and channel
            noise multiply per hop. The end-to-end pair's fidelity is repaired by a
            distillation protocol — two low-fidelity pairs in, one higher-fidelity
            pair out, with classical post-selection on local measurement
            outcomes <SourceNote id="bennett-pra-1996" />.
          </li>
        </ol>
        <p>
          The first generation runs all four steps as written. The second replaces the
          distillation step (and, where possible, the heralded-generation step) with
          quantum error correction on the memory qubits. The third drops the
          generation-and-swap pattern altogether and instead transmits a block-encoded
          quantum state directly through the chain, repairing loss at each station with
          QEC.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="gen1" data-nav-section>
        <h2>1G — heralded generation, distillation, two-way signalling</h2>
        <p>
          First-generation repeaters suppress <em>both</em> loss errors and operation
          errors probabilistically. Loss is handled by HEGP — repeat until heralded
          success — and operation errors are handled by two-way entanglement distillation
          (2-EDP). Both subprotocols require classical messages travelling between
          repeater nodes in <em>both</em> directions, which is the architectural
          signature of 1G: the time scale per success step is bounded below by
          <Math tex="\\max(L_0/c,\\, t_{\\text{op}})" />, where
          <Math tex="L_0/c" /> is the round-trip classical-signalling latency between
          adjacent nodes <SourceNote id="azuma-rmp-95" />.
        </p>
        <p>
          The canonical 1G protocol family is BDCZ (Briegel–Dür–Cirac–Zoller, 1998),
          built around <em>nested purification</em>: pairs at distance
          <Math tex="L_0" /> are distilled, then swapped to distance
          <Math tex="2L_0" />, distilled again, swapped to <Math tex="4L_0" />, and so
          on up to the full chain length. The atomic-ensemble variants pioneered by
          DLCZ (Duan–Lukin–Cirac–Zoller, 2001) and surveyed exhaustively by Sangouard
          et al. share the same control structure with photonic emission from collective
          ensemble excitations <SourceNote id="sangouard-rmp-83" />.
        </p>
        <p>
          1G is the family with the longest experimental track record — every
          memory-based repeater demonstration to date (NV centres, SiV centres, trapped
          ions, neutral atoms) is, architecturally, a 1G prototype with a small number
          of nodes. The cost is the rate scaling: the cost coefficient is
          <Math tex="\\text{poly}(L)" />, and the time scale per step is dominated by
          the classical round-trip <SourceNote id="muralidharan-scirep-2016" />.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="gen1-anim" data-nav-section>
        <h2>1G in motion — heralded generation and nested swaps</h2>
        <p>
          Five nodes — Alice, three relays <Math tex="R_1, R_2, R_3" />, and Bob — are
          connected by four short fibre segments. Each node holds matter qubits
          (green) in memory. The animation runs the three stages of a 1G cycle in
          sequence: heralded entanglement generation on every segment, then a first
          round of swaps at <Math tex="R_1" /> and <Math tex="R_3" /> in parallel,
          then a final swap at <Math tex="R_2" /> that delivers an end-to-end Bell
          pair across the chain <SourceNote id="bdcz-prl-1998" /><SourceNote id="sangouard-rmp-83" /><SourceNote id="azuma-rmp-95" />.
        </p>

        <figure class="rp-anim" data-rp>
          <div class="rp-stage-badge" data-rp-badge>EG</div>
          <svg viewBox="0 0 1100 420" role="img"
               aria-label="1G repeater architecture: four heralded entanglement-generation links between Alice, three relays, and Bob, followed by nested Bell-state measurements that fuse the links into one end-to-end Bell pair."
