          </svg>

          <ul class="rp-legend">
            <li><span class="sw-dot" style="background:#2ea043"></span>matter qubit (live)</li>
            <li><span class="sw-dot" style="background:#b0b6c0"></span>matter qubit (consumed)</li>
            <li><span class="sw-dot" style="background:#3b82f6"></span>photon, flying to BSM</li>
            <li><span class="sw-bar" style="background:#a8408d"></span>established Bell pair</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="rp-controls" data-rp-controls>
            <div class="rp-controls-row">
              <button type="button" class="rp-btn" data-rp-play aria-label="Play or pause">Pause</button>
              <input type="range" class="rp-scrub" min="0" max="1000" value="0"
                     aria-label="Scrub through the simulation stages"
                     data-rp-scrub/>
              <span class="rp-stage-name" data-rp-stage-name>EG · attempts</span>
            </div>
            <div class="rp-controls-row rp-controls-row--narrow">
              <fieldset class="rp-modes">
                <legend>Error rate</legend>
                <label><input type="radio" name="rp-mode" value="ideal"/> No errors</label>
                <label><input type="radio" name="rp-mode" value="realistic" checked/> Realistic</label>
                <label><input type="radio" name="rp-mode" value="custom"/> Custom</label>
              </fieldset>
              <div class="rp-custom" data-rp-custom hidden>
                <label>
                  <span>p<sub>EG</sub></span>
                  <input type="range" min="5" max="100" value="50" step="5" data-rp-peg/>
                  <span class="rp-val" data-rp-peg-val>0.50</span>
                </label>
                <label>
                  <span>p<sub>ES</sub></span>
                  <input type="range" min="20" max="100" value="85" step="5" data-rp-pes/>
                  <span class="rp-val" data-rp-pes-val>0.85</span>
                </label>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="rp-explain" data-rp-explain aria-live="polite">
            <p data-rp-para="EG" class="is-active">
              <strong>Heralded generation.</strong> Each pair of neighbouring matter
              qubits (green) emits a photon (blue) downwards into a shared midpoint.
              At that midpoint the two photons meet at a 50:50 beam splitter, are
              split in polarisation by the two PBS diamonds, and end at four
              single-photon detectors. A specific coincidence pattern across those
              detectors is the <em>herald</em>: when the bulb above the apparatus
              flashes green, the two distant matter qubits are now entangled. Most
              attempts fail — channel loss is exponential and a linear-optics BSM
              succeeds at most half the time even when both photons arrive — so the
              attempt counter ticks until each link finally heralds.
            </p>
            <p data-rp-para="ES1">
              <strong>First swap, in parallel at R<sub>1</sub> and R<sub>3</sub>.</strong>
              Once all four short Bell pairs are alive in memory (wavy pink lines), the
              two outer relays each perform a local Bell measurement on the two matter
              qubits they hold. That measurement, plus the classical bits it produces,
              fuses the two short pairs into one longer pair that now stretches across
              both segments. The relay's matter qubits are consumed in the process and
              fade to grey. R<sub>1</sub> and R<sub>3</sub> run independently and at the
              same time — this is the parallelism that gives the nested scheme its rate.
            </p>
            <p data-rp-para="ES2">
              <strong>Second swap at R<sub>2</sub>.</strong> The two longer pairs meet at
              the middle relay, which performs the same local Bell measurement on its two
              matter qubits. The result is a single Bell pair shared end-to-end between
              Alice and Bob. Every interior matter qubit has been consumed; the
              entanglement that started as four short, fragile, probabilistic links is now
              one long resource, ready to use for teleportation, key exchange, or any
              other Bell-pair-consuming protocol.
            </p>
            <p data-rp-para="HOLD">
              <strong>Why memories matter.</strong> Each link heralds at a random time;
              the next swap cannot run until <em>all</em> the inputs it needs are alive
              at the same moment. The matter qubits at every node hold their half of a
              successful pair while their neighbour is still retrying. Memory coherence
              time bounds how long the chain can wait before the stored pair degrades —
              the dominant practical constraint on how long a 1G chain can be made.
            </p>
          </div>

          <figcaption>
            Drag the scrubber to step through the stages, or change the error-rate
            mode to see how the per-link attempt count responds. Citations:
            BDCZ <SourceNote id="bdcz-prl-1998" />,
            Sangouard et al. <SourceNote id="sangouard-rmp-83" />,
            Azuma et al. <SourceNote id="azuma-rmp-95" />.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
      </section>

      <section id="gen2" data-nav-section>
        <h2>2G — encoded memory qubits with quantum error correction</h2>
        <p>
          Second-generation repeaters keep the heralded-generation-plus-swapping
          structure of 1G but replace probabilistic distillation with deterministic
          quantum error correction at the encoding level. Each logical memory qubit is
          encoded into a block of physical qubits (a small CSS or surface code), and
          operation errors at the swap stations are corrected by syndrome measurement
          rather than purified out by 2-EDP. Loss errors during photonic generation
          are still handled probabilistically, so two-way signalling for the
          generation step remains; the swaps and gates themselves no longer need it.
        </p>
        <p>
          The shift from 2-EDP to QEC has a measurable effect on the time scale: it
          drops from <Math tex="\\max(L/c,\\, t_0)" /> in 1G to
          <Math tex="\\max(L_0/c,\\, t_0)" /> in 2G, with
          <Math tex="L_0" /> being the inter-node spacing rather than the full distance
          <Math tex="L" />, and the cost coefficient improves to
          <Math tex="\\text{polylog}(L)" /> <SourceNote id="azuma-rmp-95" />. The
          overhead is hardware: each memory qubit is now several physical qubits, and
          each repeater node needs a fault-tolerant logical processor good enough to
          run the syndrome circuits at the code's threshold.
        </p>
        <p>
          2G has not yet been demonstrated end-to-end. The hardware requirement (logical
          memory qubits below threshold, performing local QEC continuously) is essentially
          the same as for fault-tolerant local quantum computing, which the field has
          only recently approached at the small-block-code scale.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="gen3" data-nav-section>
        <h2>3G — block-encoded transport, one-way signalling</h2>
        <p>
          Third-generation repeaters dispense with the heralded-generation-and-swap
          pattern entirely. Instead, the sender encodes a logical qubit into a block of
          physical qubits and transmits the block through the chain. Each repeater
          station applies QEC to repair both loss and operation errors before forwarding
          the block to the next station. There are no Bell pairs in the architectural
          picture, no swap operations, and — most importantly — no two-way classical
          signalling: each station processes its block and forwards it onward in one
          direction <SourceNote id="muralidharan-scirep-2016" />.
        </p>
        <p>
          The signalling change matters because it removes the
          <Math tex="L_0/c" /> latency floor that 1G and 2G inherit from their
          retry-and-confirm subprotocols. The 3G time scale per step is the local gate
          time <Math tex="t_0" /> alone, and the cost coefficient is
          <Math tex="\\text{polylog}(L)" /> <SourceNote id="azuma-rmp-95" />. In
          regimes where the bottleneck is end-to-end latency rather than hardware
          density, 3G is the architecture that wins.
        </p>
        <p>
          The hardware demand is the steepest of the three. The block code must
          tolerate at least 50 % loss per segment to break the no-cloning bound on
          deterministic loss correction (see Sec. III.B of Azuma et al.) — a high bar
          for any current photonic platform — and the QEC at each station must run at
          the line rate. 3G remains a theoretical regime, with proposed concrete
          implementations based on tree-graph codes, parity-check codes, and
          GKP-encoded continuous-variable channels but no end-to-end experimental
          demonstration.
        </p>
        <Callout label="Generations are not a sequence to walk through" tone="muted">
          <p>
            The numbering reflects increasing technological difficulty, not a fixed
            development order. A given network deployment might use 1G for some links
            and 2G for others depending on which physical platform sits at each node;
            3G remains a theoretical possibility for very-long-haul links once the
            hardware requirements (logical-qubit-rate QEC and high-loss-tolerant block
            codes) are met.
          </p>
        </Callout>
      </section>

      <section id="bsm-limit" data-nav-section>
        <h2>The 50 % linear-optics BSM ceiling</h2>
        <p>
          The Bell-state measurement is the central operation in both teleportation
          (where it consumes Alice's <Math tex="|\\psi\\rangle" /> and her half of a
          Bell pair) and in 1G/2G entanglement swapping (where it fuses two Bell pairs
          at a relay). On photonic qubits, however, a BSM done with linear optics —
          beam splitters, phase shifters, and single-photon detectors, with no
          interaction nonlinearity and no ancilla photons — cannot succeed more than
          50 % of the time. The bound is due to Calsamiglia and Lütkenhaus (2001):
          linear optics can distinguish only two of the four Bell states
          (<Math tex="|\\Psi^+\\rangle" /> and <Math tex="|\\Psi^-\\rangle" />),
          collapsing the other two into ambiguous detection patterns. Up to 50 %
          success — never more, with linear optics
          alone <SourceNote id="azuma-rmp-95" />.
        </p>
        <p>
          The 50 % ceiling is the headline cost of running 1G repeaters on photonic
          link-layer protocols. Each successful entanglement generation already burns
          <Math tex="1/P_{\\text{ent}}" /> attempts on average just from photon loss
          and detector inefficiency; the BSM ceiling halves that further at the swap
          stations, so the per-hop overhead compounds with the chain length.
        </p>
        <p>
          The ceiling is not absolute — it applies specifically to <em>linear-optics
          schemes without ancillae</em>. Adding ancilla photons (entangled or not)
          breaks the bound: a textbook scheme using one ancilla Bell pair raises the
          BSM success probability to 75 %, and Bayerbach et al. demonstrated a
          linear-optics BSM operating above the 50 % bound experimentally with two
          ancilla photons, achieving a measured success probability of about
          57.9 % <SourceNote id="bayerbach-sciadv-2023" />. These ancilla-assisted or
          "boosted" BSM schemes are the practical workaround to the linear-optics
          ceiling and are beginning to appear in repeater protocol designs.
        </p>
      </section>

